.TH ARGS(1),User Commands,ARGS(1)

.SH NAME
args - print each command-line argument

.SH SYNOPSIS
args [argument ...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
args prints each argument it receives, one per line, prefixed with a hexadecimal index and quoted.
It is primarily useful for debugging argument parsing, quoting, and word-splitting behavior in the shell.

Each line has the form [NN]: 'argument' where NN is a two-digit hex index starting at 00.

.SH EXAMPLES
$ args hello world

 [00]: 'hello'
 [01]: 'world'

.SH EXIT STATUS
args always exits 0.
